print("\nTesting erronous data in Country")

for index, row in salesClean.iterrows():
    
    #try to convert the string to a float, if sucessful not a Country
    #turn float into NULL and add to the erronous data count
    try: 
        row.loc['Country'] = float(row.loc['Country']) 
        print(salesClean.loc[int(index), 'Country'])
        salesClean.loc[int(index), 'Country'] = "NULL" 
        count += 1
    
    except:
        count += 0

print(f"Number of erronous countries {count}.")

In [6]:
#remove rows that have incorrect data
salesClean = salesClean.dropna(axis = 0) #removes all rows with missing data from 'Item Type' and 'Order Priority'
salesClean = salesClean[salesClean['Country'] != "NULL"] #removes all rows with incorrect 'Country' that was changed to NULL
salesClean = salesClean[salesClean['Order ID'] != 0] #removed all rows with incorrect "Order ID' that was changed to a 0

Getting more customers to order in-store will better profit their in house locations.

In [17]:
#Create a Boxplot using Seaborn showing the Total Profits DISTRIBUTION by Item Type.

#create boxplot
plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
sns.boxplot(x='Item Type', y='Total Profit', data=salesClean)
plt.title("Total Profit Distribution by Item Type")
plt.ticklabel_format(style='plain', axis='y')
plt.show()

This boxplot shows the total profit distribution by item type. Household, cosmetics, and office supplies bring in some of the highest average total profits, with fruits, beverages, and personal care items brining in the least total profit. In relatively all item types, the data does not seem to be skewed, nor are there any outliers. This data can be useful in knowing which products are most profitable, and which products need to be imporved or dropped from the line.

3.6¶

The boxplot shows Marvel Mart's total profit distribution by item type. The graph shows that on average, household, cosmetics, and office supplies have the highest total profit, whereas fruits, beverages and personal care have the lowest. Among all item types, we can tell that the data is not skewed because the line separating the boxes are all relatively even. We can also tell there are no outliers because no extraneous points lie beyond the wiskers.

Looking at the profit distributions by item type will help Marvel Mart determine which products are profitable and which ones are not. Marvel Mart might consider dropping fruit products becuase it does not nearly bring in as much profit as the other ityem types. This will help Marvel Mart invest their money towards only profitable products, or work towards imporving lower profitability items.

In [27]:
#lineplot showing the average and maximum for respective columns

plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))

plt.plot(['Total Revenue', 'Total Cost', 'Total Profit'], [tr.mean(), tc.mean(), tp.mean()], label='Mean')
plt.title("Average and Maximum of Total Revenue, Cost, and Profit")
plt.legend()

plt.ylabel("Dollar Amount")
plt.ticklabel_format(style='plain', axis='y')
plt.show()

This line plot shows both the maximum and the average values of Marvel Mart's total revenue, cost, and profit. Similarly to the line plot above, total revenue will ideally have a higher average and maximum than total cost. This will result in a positive total profit in both average and maximum values, as seen in the line plot above.

Region = list(set(salesClean['Region']))

countriesByRegion = {}

#loop through "Region' column and get unique 'Country'
for x in Region:
    countries = salesClean.loc[salesClean['Region'] == x, 'Country']
    countries = list(set(countries)) #removes duplicates, if any
    countriesByRegion[x] = countries

#retuns a dictionary of Countries by Region
print(countriesByRegion)
